b'' b'[from kalat, j.w.. _biological psychology_. wadsworth publishing co.' b'belmont, ca. pg. reproduced without permission.]' b'' b'' b'' b'digression miracle berries and the modification of taste receptors' b'' b'although the _miracle berry_, a plant native to west africa is practically' b'tasteless, it temporarily changes the taste of other substances. miracle' b'berries contain a protein, _miraculin_, that modifies sweet receptors in' b'such a way that they can be stimulated by acids (bartoshuk, gentile,' b'moskowitz, meiselman, if you ever get a chance to chew a miracle' b'berry (and i do recommend it), for about the next half an hour all acids' b'(which are normally sour) will taste sweet. they will continue to taste' b'sour as well.' b'' b'miraculin was, for a time, commercially available in the united states as a' b'diet aid. the idea was that dieters could coat their tongue with a miraculin' b'pill and then eat and drink unsweetened, slightly acidic substances. such' b'substances would taste sweet without providing many calories.' b'' b'a colleague and i once spent an evening experimenting with miracle berries.' b'we drank straight lemon juice, sauerkraut juice, even vinegar. all tasted' b'extremely sweet. somehow we forgot how acidic these substances are. we' b'awoke the next day to find our mouths full of ulcers.' b'' b'[... continued discussion of a couple other taste-altering substances b'' b'' b'refs:' b'' b'bartoshuk, l.m., gentile, r.l., moskowitz, h.r., meiselman, h.l. b'sweet taste induced by miracle fruit (_synsephalum dulcificum_).' b'_physiology behavior_. b'' b'' b'-------------' b'' b'' b'anyone ever hear of these things or know where to get them?' b'' b'' b'-marc' b'' b'' b'' 